1
00:00:14,500 --> 00:00:19,016
...denied reports the British
banking system is about to collapse.

2
00:00:19,100 --> 00:00:22,489
According to him, Barings' failure
is a unique situation,...

3
00:00:22,579 --> 00:00:26,458
...which he blames on the actions
of a rogue trader in Singapore.

4
00:00:26,539 --> 00:00:31,931
Estimates of potential losses range from
800 million to over one billion pounds.

5
00:00:52,856 --> 00:00:54,812
Look at that!

6
00:00:54,896 --> 00:00:56,887
Will you fuckin' look at that!

7
00:00:57,775 --> 00:00:59,925
- What, with the black guy?
- Yeah.

8
00:01:01,775 --> 00:01:04,209
It's a shame.
She looks well spoken for.

9
00:01:05,015 --> 00:01:07,403
Never know your luck, though.
Eh, mate?

10
00:01:07,494 --> 00:01:11,203
- Think I'll give her the treatment!
- No, Steve, no. Don't do that.

11
00:01:11,294 --> 00:01:14,206
- No, you're all right.
- Don't do that. Steve. Steve!

12
00:01:17,453 --> 00:01:20,047
Hello, love.
I've got something to show ya.

13
00:01:24,093 --> 00:01:27,209
Are you out of your mind or what?
You fuckin' little prick!

14
00:01:27,292 --> 00:01:29,248
And I mean little!

15
00:01:29,332 --> 00:01:31,721
Don't judge a book
by its cover, sweetheart.

16
00:01:31,812 --> 00:01:34,610
- You're out of your league, arsehole.
- Calm down.

17
00:01:34,692 --> 00:01:36,443
Fuck off or you're dead!

18
00:01:36,531 --> 00:01:39,329
- I want you out of here, now.
- He's really sorry.

19
00:01:39,411 --> 00:01:43,529
He's pissed. He meant no disrespect.
That's the last thing on anybody's mind.

20
00:01:43,611 --> 00:01:46,124
Tell him if he doesn't
put that thing away,...

21
00:01:46,210 --> 00:01:49,088
...I'll rip it off and shove it
down his fuckin' throat!

22
00:01:49,170 --> 00:01:52,719
Do your flies up, you fuckin' animal.
You almost gave me a heart attack.

23
00:01:54,210 --> 00:01:57,758
Just leave it.
It's not worth it!

24
00:01:57,849 --> 00:02:00,044
He's done it again.
I had to pull him off!

25
00:02:00,129 --> 00:02:01,881
Fuckin' right laugh!

26
00:02:04,409 --> 00:02:07,559
Aagghh!
Aagghh!

27
00:02:10,848 --> 00:02:12,804
Nick!
Nick!

28
00:02:12,888 --> 00:02:14,878
You all right?
Nick!

29
00:02:31,006 --> 00:02:34,554
It was thanks to Maggie Thatcher
opening up the City of London...

30
00:02:34,645 --> 00:02:40,117
...that yours truly from Watford came to be
working for a posh outfit like Barings.

31
00:02:41,325 --> 00:02:45,795
That was me lying on the floor,
if you hadn't guessed. Nick Leeson.

32
00:02:45,884 --> 00:02:47,875
You've probably heard about me.

33
00:02:52,084 --> 00:02:54,802
Barings was the oldest
private bank in the world.

34
00:02:54,883 --> 00:02:59,434
They financed the Louisiana Purchase
back in eighteen hundred and something.

35
00:02:59,523 --> 00:03:02,594
They even had the
Queen as a customer!

36
00:03:07,202 --> 00:03:09,158
I was just a humble clerk.

37
00:03:09,242 --> 00:03:11,153
But not for long, I hoped.

38
00:03:11,921 --> 00:03:13,798
Car crash.

39
00:03:13,881 --> 00:03:17,032
I hit my head on the back of
the seat and broke my nose.

40
00:03:17,121 --> 00:03:21,272
Everybody else was all right cos they
were wearing their, um... seat belts.

41
00:03:21,360 --> 00:03:23,351
Poor chap!

42
00:03:23,960 --> 00:03:29,318
Nick, I know you're keen to get out of the
back office and onto the trading floor,...

43
00:03:29,400 --> 00:03:32,391
...but in the meantime
something else has come up.

44
00:03:32,479 --> 00:03:34,993
We've got problems
in our Jakarta office.

45
00:03:35,079 --> 00:03:38,151
We need someone to go out there
and sort things out.

46
00:03:38,239 --> 00:03:40,149
I thought that someone might be...

47
00:03:40,238 --> 00:03:41,751
...Nick Leeson?

48
00:03:47,518 --> 00:03:50,509
Indonesia was one of the
new "tiger economies"...

49
00:03:50,597 --> 00:03:53,031
...everyone was getting
so excited about.

50
00:03:53,117 --> 00:03:55,790
"Emerging markets"
they were calling them,...

51
00:03:55,877 --> 00:03:59,152
...and Barings was one of the first
to see their potential.

52
00:04:00,036 --> 00:04:02,789
The rewards were high.
But so were the risks.

53
00:04:04,476 --> 00:04:06,353
One hundred million pounds...

54
00:04:06,436 --> 00:04:08,108
...in bearer bonds.

55
00:04:08,196 --> 00:04:09,753
As good as cash.

56
00:04:09,835 --> 00:04:11,712
We could pick 'em up,
walk out,...

57
00:04:11,795 --> 00:04:14,468
...come to some arrangement
with laughing boy...

58
00:04:14,555 --> 00:04:16,432
Customers refuse to pay for them.

59
00:04:16,515 --> 00:04:19,506
They say what's on them doesn't
match the original deal.

60
00:04:19,594 --> 00:04:23,030
The real reason: the market goes down,
they don't want any more.

61
00:04:23,114 --> 00:04:24,945
It's a mess.

62
00:04:25,034 --> 00:04:29,743
You're absolutely 100 per cent right,
Susi. It's one hell of a fuckin' mess.

63
00:04:36,473 --> 00:04:38,827
It was my job to sort out
the certificates...

64
00:04:38,912 --> 00:04:42,188
...so customers wouldn't have
any more excuses not to pay.

65
00:04:42,272 --> 00:04:46,151
Until then, Barings had this bloody
great hole in their balance sheet.

66
00:04:46,232 --> 00:04:49,268
It was boring work, but I knew
if I made a success of it...

67
00:04:49,351 --> 00:04:51,307
...then I could write my own ticket.

68
00:04:51,391 --> 00:04:54,269
All the certificates are in
the right denomination.

69
00:04:54,351 --> 00:04:58,104
I've sorted out all the documentation.
That's all in order now, so...

70
00:04:58,190 --> 00:04:59,908
...all I need from you...

71
00:04:59,990 --> 00:05:01,708
...is a cheque!

72
00:05:15,509 --> 00:05:17,499
Hello.
I'm Lisa.

73
00:05:22,348 --> 00:05:24,464
I'm, um... Nick Leeson.
Can I help you?

74
00:05:24,548 --> 00:05:27,061
Barings sent me to help
with the settlements.

75
00:05:27,147 --> 00:05:28,705
Didn't they tell you?

76
00:05:28,787 --> 00:05:34,180
Oh, of course! I've been on at them for so
long I never thought they'd get round to it.

77
00:05:34,267 --> 00:05:36,575
What do we do with that lot?
Build a bonfire?

78
00:05:42,506 --> 00:05:45,975
I'd never even heard of Barings
before I started working for 'em.

79
00:05:46,065 --> 00:05:48,374
It's not like there's
a Barings in Watford.

80
00:05:48,465 --> 00:05:52,060
You're a hero in London. They think
the sun shines out of your arse.

81
00:05:52,145 --> 00:05:56,217
Really? I was beginning to feel like
one of those Japanese soldiers.

82
00:05:56,304 --> 00:05:59,501
Still stuck out in the jungle
20 years after the war!

83
00:05:59,584 --> 00:06:02,781
What's it like here?
They tell me it's not safe at night.

84
00:06:02,864 --> 00:06:04,819
Bollocks.
The locals are great.

85
00:06:04,903 --> 00:06:09,977
And it's not full of pompous ex-colonials
thinking they were born to rule the world.

86
00:06:10,063 --> 00:06:11,894
That's what I love about Asia.

87
00:06:12,703 --> 00:06:16,012
Anyone can make it. Doesn't
matter which school you went to.

88
00:06:16,102 --> 00:06:19,697
When they told me I was going to
Jakarta I had to look it up on the map.

89
00:06:20,982 --> 00:06:22,972
As a matter of fact, so did I.

90
00:06:24,501 --> 00:06:26,093
I really want to be a trader.

91
00:06:26,181 --> 00:06:29,139
If Barings don't let me on
the floor after this, I'm off.

92
00:06:29,221 --> 00:06:33,054
- Not gonna be bloody clerking all my life.
- Ooh! Ambitious, aren't we?

93
00:06:33,140 --> 00:06:35,051
- Is that bad?
- It's great.

94
00:06:35,140 --> 00:06:36,971
I just want to get on in life.

95
00:06:37,060 --> 00:06:41,019
I like to enjoy myself, don't get me wrong.
Work hard, play hard.

96
00:06:41,460 --> 00:06:43,450
Well, I think this is me.

97
00:06:45,019 --> 00:06:47,658
Well, night, Nick.
That was fun.

98
00:06:48,699 --> 00:06:51,008
Yeah, it was, wasn't it?

99
00:06:51,099 --> 00:06:53,771
- OK. Night-night!
- See you tomorrow, then.

100
00:06:55,818 --> 00:06:57,774
Lisa was a stunner all right.

101
00:06:57,858 --> 00:06:59,814
Love at first sight.

102
00:06:59,898 --> 00:07:03,207
Together we made short work
of the rest of those bonds.

103
00:07:03,297 --> 00:07:07,575
Soon we cleared up most of Barings'
losses and it was time to go home.

104
00:07:07,657 --> 00:07:09,375
See you later, Lisa.

105
00:07:09,457 --> 00:07:11,492
Bye.

106
00:07:32,534 --> 00:07:35,571
I think you'll agree that in Nick
Lisa has met her prince.

107
00:07:35,654 --> 00:07:37,246
Hear!
Hear!

108
00:07:37,334 --> 00:07:40,769
Join me in wishing them well
in their new life in Singapore,...

109
00:07:40,853 --> 00:07:45,529
...where Nick is to be general manager of
the trading floor. Whatever that means.

110
00:07:45,613 --> 00:07:48,524
It impressed the hell
out of me, but...

111
00:07:48,612 --> 00:07:49,886
And, um...

112
00:07:49,972 --> 00:07:53,282
To you, Nick, I'm entrusting
the most precious of gifts.

113
00:07:53,372 --> 00:07:56,205
I know you're gonna look after her
and cherish her...

114
00:07:56,292 --> 00:07:58,851
...and all those other things.
And if you don't,...

115
00:08:00,771 --> 00:08:03,001
...I'll break your bloody legs, all right?

116
00:08:03,891 --> 00:08:05,404
He means it!

117
00:08:06,091 --> 00:08:08,046
I love you so much, Lisa Leeson.

118
00:08:08,130 --> 00:08:10,325
I love you too, Nick.

119
00:08:16,930 --> 00:08:21,286
As a reward for Jakarta I'd been given the
far more important market of Singapore,...

120
00:08:21,369 --> 00:08:24,884
...with a brief to set up my
own trading operation.

121
00:08:25,729 --> 00:08:27,764
I was definitely on my way.

122
00:08:37,047 --> 00:08:40,164
- And the kitchen...
- This is your department, darling.

123
00:08:40,247 --> 00:08:42,238
Since when?
Cheeky!

124
00:08:43,727 --> 00:08:45,718
And the bedroom...

125
00:09:00,645 --> 00:09:03,398
- If you need anything, call me.
- Right, thanks.

126
00:09:03,485 --> 00:09:05,440
- Have a nice day.
- Thanks. Bye.

127
00:09:05,524 --> 00:09:07,515
Goodbye.

128
00:09:08,804 --> 00:09:11,364
Not bad for a chancer
from Watford, eh?

129
00:09:11,444 --> 00:09:14,799
Well, um... I think we should
test out that mattress, big boy.

130
00:09:14,883 --> 00:09:16,874
- Oh, yeah?
- Yeah!

131
00:09:21,523 --> 00:09:23,514
Whoo!

132
00:09:40,441 --> 00:09:44,718
I can't see any problem in you
handling both sides of the operation.

133
00:09:44,800 --> 00:09:47,360
- At least until volumes increase.
- Right.

134
00:09:47,440 --> 00:09:50,238
You shouldn't need more than two
on the trading floor.

135
00:09:50,320 --> 00:09:52,231
A couple more in the back office.

136
00:09:52,320 --> 00:09:54,150
No need to pay top dollar.

137
00:09:54,239 --> 00:09:56,992
Get them young, get them hungry
and train them up.

138
00:09:57,079 --> 00:10:01,630
- I'm a bottom line kind of guy, Nick.
- Absolutely. That's my philosophy.

139
00:10:02,199 --> 00:10:05,156
I took him at his word.
My team were young, hungry...

140
00:10:05,238 --> 00:10:06,956
...and they didn't have a clue.

141
00:10:07,038 --> 00:10:11,828
A futures contract allows you to buy or
sell a specified amount of a commodity...

142
00:10:11,917 --> 00:10:14,306
...at a specified price
at a future date.

143
00:10:17,797 --> 00:10:19,628
Right.
Um...

144
00:10:19,717 --> 00:10:24,232
It's like, if I agree to sell you this cup
of cappuccino, which I don't yet own,...

145
00:10:24,316 --> 00:10:26,352
...at 45 cents a month from now...

146
00:10:26,436 --> 00:10:30,634
If I can buy the cappuccino at,
say, 43 cents, I make a profit.

147
00:10:30,716 --> 00:10:34,025
If the price goes the other way
I have to pay more, and I lose.

148
00:10:34,115 --> 00:10:36,993
It's timing - buying and selling
at the right moment.

149
00:10:37,075 --> 00:10:40,306
Sometimes espresso might be
the best deal, or salt, or pepper.

150
00:10:40,395 --> 00:10:42,464
So, we're running a supermarket?

151
00:10:44,674 --> 00:10:47,029
We're not buying and selling
anything real.

152
00:10:47,114 --> 00:10:50,628
It's just numbers - contracts
based on the value of the Nikkei,...

153
00:10:50,713 --> 00:10:52,431
...the Tokyo stock market.

154
00:10:52,513 --> 00:10:55,869
- Er, we do this for the bank?
- No, no, for the customers.

155
00:10:55,953 --> 00:10:58,911
We are not allowed to trade
on behalf of the bank.

156
00:10:58,993 --> 00:11:01,426
Be sure you remember that, all right?

157
00:11:02,112 --> 00:11:06,151
Other dealers wear red jackets.
All same. Red is lucky Chinese colour.

158
00:11:06,232 --> 00:11:10,110
Well, we want to stand out. We're a
new operation. We need to be noticed.

159
00:11:10,191 --> 00:11:12,147
May be bad luck.
Different colour.

160
00:11:12,231 --> 00:11:14,142
Bollocks.
We make our own luck.

161
00:11:14,231 --> 00:11:17,507
Nick's right.
We're cool dudes, man. Whoo!

162
00:11:53,427 --> 00:11:55,987
Fernando.
Anything happening in Tokyo?

163
00:11:56,067 --> 00:11:57,818
Nothin'.
How's SIMEX?

164
00:11:59,066 --> 00:12:00,977
Same here.
No one's playin'.

165
00:12:01,066 --> 00:12:03,057
590, and trading small.

166
00:12:03,146 --> 00:12:04,943
600, and thin too.

167
00:12:07,705 --> 00:12:11,380
580 here. There's a seller who wants
to trade in size. Shall I low-tick him?

168
00:12:11,465 --> 00:12:13,057
Yeah.
Flush him out.

169
00:12:13,625 --> 00:12:16,502
- Squeeze the sucker.
- How many?

170
00:12:16,584 --> 00:12:17,903
200.

171
00:12:17,984 --> 00:12:19,656
Buy them... now.

172
00:12:20,424 --> 00:12:22,096
- Buy 'em!
- Filled!

173
00:12:23,224 --> 00:12:25,021
We paid 580 for 200.

174
00:12:25,104 --> 00:12:27,492
Way to go, Nick! I sold at 590.

175
00:12:28,223 --> 00:12:30,691
Fuck a duck!
Just made 2,000 quid.

176
00:12:30,783 --> 00:12:32,421
Yes!

177
00:12:39,222 --> 00:12:42,134
They were a good bunch and
they were keen to learn.

178
00:12:43,422 --> 00:12:47,494
It looked like a madhouse with
all the traders waving and shouting,...

179
00:12:47,581 --> 00:12:50,459
...but it all made sense once
you got the hang of it.

180
00:12:50,541 --> 00:12:53,613
There were hiccups, but that's
normal in any operation,...

181
00:12:53,701 --> 00:12:56,373
...especially a new one like ours.

182
00:12:57,820 --> 00:13:01,210
The important thing was we
were picking up the business...

183
00:13:01,300 --> 00:13:03,291
...and the future looked rosy.

184
00:13:15,738 --> 00:13:20,414
Nick, what's the difference between
initial margin and variation margin?

185
00:13:20,498 --> 00:13:24,456
Initial margin's a down payment on
each futures contract that we trade.

186
00:13:24,537 --> 00:13:26,812
We don't pay in full until
a contract matures.

187
00:13:26,897 --> 00:13:30,572
But in the meantime the value of
each contract may go up or down.

188
00:13:30,657 --> 00:13:33,807
So SIMEX calculate our positions
on a daily basis.

189
00:13:33,896 --> 00:13:38,128
They'll ask for more money if the market
goes against us. That's variation margin.

190
00:13:38,216 --> 00:13:40,605
Got it.
I think!

191
00:13:43,775 --> 00:13:47,370
We need to open an errors account.
We've had a few mistakes.

192
00:13:47,455 --> 00:13:50,572
I need somewhere to put them
till I can write them out.

193
00:13:50,655 --> 00:13:53,248
Sure. What number shall I give it?

194
00:13:53,334 --> 00:13:57,168
- Well, what's your lucky number?
- Eight. It is a very lucky Chinese number.

195
00:13:57,254 --> 00:13:59,688
And how many numbers
do we need?

196
00:13:59,774 --> 00:14:00,923
Five.

197
00:14:01,014 --> 00:14:05,131
Then let's give it all the luck it can
handle. Call it the 88888 account.

198
00:14:26,731 --> 00:14:32,726
And now it gives me great pleasure to
welcome the chairman of Barings Bank,...

199
00:14:33,050 --> 00:14:35,041
...Peter Baring.

200
00:14:43,489 --> 00:14:46,208
We may be the oldest merchant
bank in the world,...

201
00:14:46,289 --> 00:14:50,247
...but that's no excuse for not
keeping up with the times.

202
00:14:50,328 --> 00:14:52,284
When I became chairman,...

203
00:14:52,368 --> 00:14:56,759
...I realised we couldn't go on running
Barings like a gentlemen's club.

204
00:14:56,848 --> 00:15:01,125
We had to look beyond our
traditional recruiting grounds,...

205
00:15:01,207 --> 00:15:03,277
...the old school tie,...

206
00:15:03,367 --> 00:15:06,439
...to seek out a new
and hungrier breed.

207
00:15:07,407 --> 00:15:11,843
We're beginning to see the fruits
of those efforts, and I have to say,...

208
00:15:11,926 --> 00:15:17,717
...the recovery in profitability, since
the reorganisation, has been... amazing.

209
00:15:17,805 --> 00:15:22,435
To be frank, I've discovered it's
not actually terribly difficult...

210
00:15:22,525 --> 00:15:25,244
...to make money in
the securities business!

211
00:15:35,404 --> 00:15:36,632
Filled.

212
00:15:46,682 --> 00:15:48,673
Yeah, you paid 50 for 20.

213
00:15:50,082 --> 00:15:52,676
Come in.

214
00:15:53,402 --> 00:15:55,597
Simon, er...
I've got a slight problem.

215
00:15:55,682 --> 00:16:00,118
One of the girls sold 20 contracts
for Fuji Bank instead of buying.

216
00:16:00,201 --> 00:16:02,351
I can't do anything
about it till Monday.

217
00:16:02,441 --> 00:16:03,920
What's the damage?

218
00:16:05,281 --> 00:16:07,271
20,000 at the close.

219
00:16:10,200 --> 00:16:12,953
Sack the cow. She'll never
work on SIMEX again.

220
00:16:13,600 --> 00:16:15,510
That's a bit hard, isn't it?

221
00:16:15,599 --> 00:16:17,635
Look, you handle it.

222
00:16:17,719 --> 00:16:21,871
Have a word with London,
but make sure you make that client good.

223
00:16:23,519 --> 00:16:25,748
All right.

224
00:16:30,518 --> 00:16:32,474
Hey!
Have a beer, shithead!

225
00:16:32,558 --> 00:16:33,991
Cheers.

226
00:16:34,078 --> 00:16:35,988
Hi, darling.

227
00:16:36,077 --> 00:16:38,272
Anyone seen Kim?

228
00:16:38,357 --> 00:16:40,632
She was here a minute ago.

229
00:16:45,956 --> 00:16:47,947
Kim...

230
00:16:48,876 --> 00:16:50,832
Nick, Nick...

231
00:16:50,916 --> 00:16:52,907
I'm really sorry. I got so confused.

232
00:16:52,996 --> 00:16:55,987
- Everybody was shouting all at once.
- That's the job.

233
00:16:56,075 --> 00:16:59,033
That's what it's all about,
keeping a cool head.

234
00:16:59,115 --> 00:17:01,424
I'm so sorry! I'll pay
you back the money.

235
00:17:01,515 --> 00:17:06,224
Sure, Kim. Four years' salary? And if
the market moves it could be even worse.

236
00:17:08,114 --> 00:17:09,752
Come on, come on.

237
00:17:09,834 --> 00:17:11,790
Come on,
everyone makes mistakes.

238
00:17:13,153 --> 00:17:17,112
Look, with a bit of luck I can trade
out of it on Monday, all right?

239
00:17:18,113 --> 00:17:22,264
Nick, I've been waiting for you while
everyone else is having a good time.

240
00:17:22,352 --> 00:17:24,343
- I'm going home now.
- Kim!

241
00:17:25,832 --> 00:17:27,982
Kim...!

242
00:17:34,111 --> 00:17:36,545
- Everything all right?
- Never better.

243
00:17:38,111 --> 00:17:42,467
Why don't you let me come in and help?
I can't sit around all day doing nothing.

244
00:17:42,550 --> 00:17:44,541
It's not a problem, Lisa.

245
00:17:45,150 --> 00:17:47,141
I can handle it.

246
00:17:52,989 --> 00:17:55,583
Fernando, how are
March futures looking?

247
00:17:55,669 --> 00:17:59,708
- I need 20 contracts at Friday's price.
- You won't get Friday's price!

248
00:17:59,789 --> 00:18:02,825
I should have closed off the position
and taken the loss.

249
00:18:02,908 --> 00:18:05,138
Instead, I waited for
the market to change.

250
00:18:05,228 --> 00:18:07,662
It changed all right,
but not the way I wanted.

251
00:18:07,748 --> 00:18:11,899
Now I was stuck with a bigger loss than
I could own up to. And it was all my fault.

252
00:18:11,987 --> 00:18:14,979
Nick! I hear your girl
handed in her notice.

253
00:18:15,067 --> 00:18:17,535
Never came back.
She couldn't stand the pace.

254
00:18:17,627 --> 00:18:19,265
So much for loyalty!

255
00:18:19,346 --> 00:18:23,305
- Did you make the client good?
- Of course. Made a small profit, actually.

256
00:18:23,386 --> 00:18:25,377
Good man.

257
00:18:29,585 --> 00:18:32,258
This one's for the
five eights account.

258
00:18:32,345 --> 00:18:34,381
I bought the missing contracts.

259
00:18:34,465 --> 00:18:35,818
60,000?

260
00:18:35,905 --> 00:18:38,021
- Shh!
- It was only 20 before.

261
00:18:38,105 --> 00:18:41,016
And the market went the wrong way.
I had to cut the loss.

262
00:18:41,104 --> 00:18:43,060
What did Simon Jones say?

263
00:18:43,144 --> 00:18:45,100
Are you serious?
He'd shut us down if he knew.

264
00:18:45,184 --> 00:18:48,892
It'll be all right so long as we balance
the books by the end of the month.

265
00:18:48,983 --> 00:18:51,019
- How? - We trade on
our own account...

266
00:18:51,103 --> 00:18:55,176
...until we wipe out the losses, then
we use money from the client account...

267
00:18:55,263 --> 00:18:57,651
...and pay it back with
next month's profits.

268
00:18:57,742 --> 00:18:59,300
You mean, gamble?

269
00:19:00,142 --> 00:19:03,214
Relax, Bonnie.
That's all the market is.

270
00:19:03,302 --> 00:19:05,497
One giant casino!

271
00:19:11,621 --> 00:19:13,179
George!

272
00:19:13,901 --> 00:19:18,132
I was counting on nobody looking at
the books until the end of each month.

273
00:19:18,220 --> 00:19:22,213
As long as the five eights account had a
nil balance on the last day of the month,...

274
00:19:22,300 --> 00:19:25,098
...no one would suspect
that anything was wrong.

275
00:19:25,180 --> 00:19:28,410
But instead of winning back the
position we made more losses,...

276
00:19:28,499 --> 00:19:32,378
...and I had to borrow more money
from the client account to hide them.

277
00:19:41,658 --> 00:19:45,969
Fuckin' hell, George, what are
you playing at? Get fuckin' out!

278
00:19:46,057 --> 00:19:48,048
Get fuckin' out!
Now!

279
00:19:49,697 --> 00:19:52,928
What the hell are you playing at?
Out! Get out!

280
00:19:54,976 --> 00:19:56,967
Fuckin' hell!

281
00:19:59,576 --> 00:20:02,568
- Agh. - God, you're tense.
Stiff as a board.

282
00:20:02,656 --> 00:20:07,012
If you only knew! All cos those bastards
won't let me hire proper staff.

283
00:20:07,095 --> 00:20:10,690
- I thought it was going so well.
- It is. It's going brilliant.

284
00:20:10,775 --> 00:20:14,210
I just spend most of my life
covering everybody else's arse.

285
00:20:14,294 --> 00:20:17,206
Well, why don't you let me
help with the back office?

286
00:20:17,294 --> 00:20:19,683
- I'm bored being a
lady of leisure. - No.

287
00:20:19,774 --> 00:20:24,005
Why not? It's ridiculous, you having
to handle trading and settlements.

288
00:20:24,093 --> 00:20:26,004
You'll have a nervous breakdown.

289
00:20:26,093 --> 00:20:28,482
I don't want you interfering.
I can handle it.

290
00:20:28,573 --> 00:20:32,248
All right, keep your pants on!
No one's saying you can't.

291
00:20:33,013 --> 00:20:37,244
I'm not going back to being a bloody clerk.
I'd rather be a plasterer.

292
00:20:38,972 --> 00:20:42,089
My mum always used to say
I could be anything I wanted,...

293
00:20:42,172 --> 00:20:44,924
...so long as I took my chances -
and worked like a dog.

294
00:20:45,011 --> 00:20:48,287
Well, you have. You've worked
really hard and it paid off.

295
00:20:48,371 --> 00:20:50,168
She'd have been so proud of you.

296
00:20:50,251 --> 00:20:52,480
Do you really think so?

297
00:20:52,970 --> 00:20:54,688
Yeah.

298
00:20:54,770 --> 00:20:56,567
I know I am!

299
00:21:01,010 --> 00:21:05,241
That was the worst part -
Lisa thinking I was this brilliant success.

300
00:21:06,089 --> 00:21:09,286
If she only knew what a
fuck-up I really was!

301
00:21:09,369 --> 00:21:11,802
When I wanted the market
to go up, it went down.

302
00:21:11,888 --> 00:21:13,958
If I wanted it to go down,
it went up.

303
00:21:14,368 --> 00:21:16,802
It was hard not to
take it personally.

304
00:21:26,247 --> 00:21:27,726
Nick?

305
00:21:27,807 --> 00:21:31,162
Nick! I just worked out the balance
in the eights account.

306
00:21:31,246 --> 00:21:35,000
- The losses are over $10 million!
- Keep your fuckin' voice down!

307
00:21:35,086 --> 00:21:37,077
Look, there's no need to panic.

308
00:21:38,166 --> 00:21:42,636
There's not enough in the client account
to make margin payments, Nick.

309
00:21:45,845 --> 00:21:47,437
Right.

310
00:21:50,324 --> 00:21:54,522
I need dollars. I need dollars to
cover the initial margin payment!

311
00:21:55,164 --> 00:21:59,873
I can get dollars from London to cover all
the client positions for the futures I buy!

312
00:21:59,963 --> 00:22:03,672
Nothing unusual about that.
But I'm gonna need yen.

313
00:22:03,763 --> 00:22:06,800
Gonna need yen to cover
the daily variation columns!

314
00:22:06,883 --> 00:22:10,079
Which'll leave a yen deficit
by the end of the month.

315
00:22:10,682 --> 00:22:13,435
Unless... unless I sell options.

316
00:22:13,922 --> 00:22:16,231
That'll generate commission in yen.

317
00:22:16,962 --> 00:22:20,920
And return the balance sheet
on the five eights account to zero!

318
00:22:23,801 --> 00:22:28,112
As long as London kept sending out
money to finance the client positions,...

319
00:22:28,200 --> 00:22:31,670
...I'd have enough cash to stay
on top of the margin payments.

320
00:22:32,360 --> 00:22:34,874
It was like robbing
Peter to pay Paul,...

321
00:22:35,480 --> 00:22:40,678
...but hopefully I'd end up making enough
to pay Peter back before he found out.

322
00:22:40,759 --> 00:22:45,389
Meanwhile I had to generate more and
more business to justify my cash calls,...

323
00:22:45,479 --> 00:22:47,628
...and for that I needed customers.

324
00:22:48,918 --> 00:22:50,909
The bigger the better.

325
00:22:59,477 --> 00:23:01,468
Mm-hm.
Oui.

326
00:23:03,397 --> 00:23:05,353
Bon, tres bien.

327
00:23:05,437 --> 00:23:07,154
Mr Leeson.

328
00:23:07,236 --> 00:23:09,670
- I'm Pierre Beaumarchais.
- Nice to meet you.

329
00:23:09,756 --> 00:23:12,987
I work for the Geneva Banking Trust,
based in the Bahamas.

330
00:23:13,676 --> 00:23:17,065
I was speaking with Ang Swee Tian,
president of SIMEX.

331
00:23:17,155 --> 00:23:20,670
He's impressed by the amount of
business you've been generating.

332
00:23:20,755 --> 00:23:23,349
- There's a lot of opportunities
here. - Oh, yes.

333
00:23:24,395 --> 00:23:26,385
I do a lot of business on SIMEX.

334
00:23:26,954 --> 00:23:29,149
With the exception
of George Soros,...

335
00:23:29,234 --> 00:23:32,146
...I probably trade in the Nikkei
more than anyone.

336
00:23:32,234 --> 00:23:35,305
Sometimes over 5,000
contracts in a day.

337
00:23:35,393 --> 00:23:38,829
That is a lot. The whole
market only does about 20.

338
00:23:40,113 --> 00:23:43,185
Could Barings handle
that amount of business?

339
00:23:46,552 --> 00:23:48,588
You bet we could!

340
00:23:48,672 --> 00:23:51,232
Beaumarchais was the
answer to my prayers.

341
00:23:51,312 --> 00:23:53,872
I'd be able to siphon off
enough commission...

342
00:23:53,951 --> 00:23:57,261
...to square the eights account
once and for all.

343
00:23:58,471 --> 00:24:00,666
- Hello?
- Pierre Beaumarchais.

344
00:24:00,751 --> 00:24:03,265
I want to buy 4,000
June contracts.

345
00:24:04,710 --> 00:24:07,508
I've... got a price of 350,
but this'll move it.

346
00:24:07,590 --> 00:24:10,104
Try not to pay more than 400.

347
00:24:10,190 --> 00:24:13,022
We gotta get them cheap.
Beaumarchais is a big player.

348
00:24:13,109 --> 00:24:15,703
If we pull this off,
we get a shitload of business.

349
00:24:15,789 --> 00:24:18,349
- What's liquidity like?
- Tight as a flea's arse.

350
00:24:18,429 --> 00:24:21,102
We'll get away with 500,
then the price will move up.

351
00:24:21,189 --> 00:24:24,464
OK. But then we'll make the other
traders think we're sellers.

352
00:24:24,548 --> 00:24:26,857
And when the price drops...
buy! All right?

353
00:24:26,948 --> 00:24:28,540
OK.

354
00:24:37,387 --> 00:24:39,503
Sell 250!

355
00:24:39,587 --> 00:24:41,305
Sell 250!
Sell 250!

356
00:24:41,387 --> 00:24:43,138
Sell 240!

357
00:24:43,226 --> 00:24:45,740
Sell 240!
Sell 240!

358
00:24:51,106 --> 00:24:53,300
Sell 200!
Sell 200!

359
00:24:57,345 --> 00:24:59,654
- Buy 500 contracts!
- Sell 200!

360
00:25:00,745 --> 00:25:02,462
Buy? Buy?

361
00:25:02,544 --> 00:25:05,502
Buy at 200! Buy at 200!
Buy at 210!

362
00:25:05,584 --> 00:25:07,575
Buy at 210!
Buy at 220!

363
00:25:08,784 --> 00:25:10,978
Buy at 220!
Buy at 230!

364
00:25:12,943 --> 00:25:14,581
Buy at 240!

365
00:25:14,663 --> 00:25:16,654
Buy at 240!
Buy at 240!

366
00:25:20,302 --> 00:25:21,940
Filled!

367
00:25:26,102 --> 00:25:30,538
Nobody saw us coming! We swooped
on the first 1500 like a Stealth bomber!

368
00:25:30,621 --> 00:25:32,452
4,000 contracts!

369
00:25:32,541 --> 00:25:35,533
Balls of steel, Fat Boy.
Balls of fuckin' steel!

370
00:25:53,059 --> 00:25:57,257
At last my luck had changed.
Suddenly I couldn't stop making money.

371
00:25:57,979 --> 00:26:02,130
I was long in the Nikkei - that meant
gambling on it going up - and up it went.

372
00:26:03,218 --> 00:26:05,209
Up and up and up.

373
00:26:10,577 --> 00:26:13,171
That's very good!
Very good.

374
00:26:15,457 --> 00:26:17,447
Serves you right, Lisa!

375
00:26:30,415 --> 00:26:35,489
If it went all the way up to 19,000, I stood
to make a killing on the options I'd sold.

376
00:26:38,894 --> 00:26:42,330
Come on, come on!
Come on, baby, you can do it. Come on.

377
00:26:43,974 --> 00:26:45,964
- Yes!
- Yes!

378
00:26:49,893 --> 00:26:53,363
Bonnie, we're on a fuckin' roll!

379
00:26:53,453 --> 00:26:55,444
Yes!

380
00:26:56,372 --> 00:26:58,328
Do you think we'll do it?

381
00:27:05,771 --> 00:27:08,444
It's amazing!
You've made back all the losses.

382
00:27:08,531 --> 00:27:12,763
- Over $10 million. - What did I tell you?
Oh, ye of little faith!

383
00:27:12,851 --> 00:27:15,569
You keep doubling up,
and sooner or later...

384
00:27:15,650 --> 00:27:17,686
...you're bound to win.

385
00:27:22,730 --> 00:27:25,687
The Nikkei has closed up
for the third day in a row,...

386
00:27:25,769 --> 00:27:29,205
...and the rally shows little sign
of running out of steam.

387
00:27:29,289 --> 00:27:32,759
Analysts are predicting additional
gains in the days ahead.

388
00:27:41,968 --> 00:27:43,923
- Happy?
- Yeah. Are you?

389
00:27:44,007 --> 00:27:45,838
Never better.

390
00:27:48,727 --> 00:27:52,686
I have been sailing a bit close to the wind.
I didn't want to worry you with it.

391
00:27:53,326 --> 00:27:55,476
- What do you mean?
- No, it's all right.

392
00:27:55,566 --> 00:27:59,081
The market turned round and a whole
load of my positions came good.

393
00:27:59,166 --> 00:28:01,043
I made it all back.

394
00:28:01,126 --> 00:28:03,116
What are you on about, Nick?

395
00:28:04,405 --> 00:28:08,683
Don't get your knickers in a twist, but we
made mistakes and ran up some losses.

396
00:28:08,765 --> 00:28:11,154
I went out on a limb to
get back the position.

397
00:28:11,245 --> 00:28:13,075
How big were the losses?

398
00:28:14,244 --> 00:28:16,678
- It's about a million.
- A million quid?!

399
00:28:17,444 --> 00:28:19,435
For God's sake, Nick!

400
00:28:20,644 --> 00:28:23,794
No, it's all right. It paid off.
I squared it up.

401
00:28:24,323 --> 00:28:26,314
I had to do it to protect the guys.

402
00:28:28,563 --> 00:28:31,076
Promise me that you'll
never do that again.

403
00:28:31,162 --> 00:28:33,722
- It's not worth it, Nick.
- I promise.

404
00:28:35,522 --> 00:28:37,513
You will give me a heart attack.

405
00:28:42,321 --> 00:28:45,074
- Merry Christmas.
- Merry Christmas.

406
00:28:52,880 --> 00:28:54,871
Fuck off!

407
00:28:56,960 --> 00:29:01,635
I really meant it. I was the number one
trader, and as the new year came in...

408
00:29:01,719 --> 00:29:05,075
...I was determined to kick my
addiction to the eights account.

409
00:29:05,159 --> 00:29:07,036
What will the market do?
Long-term?

410
00:29:07,119 --> 00:29:09,791
No one thinks long-term,
they think nanoseconds!

411
00:29:09,878 --> 00:29:12,551
- Long-term's tomorrow morning.
- Tomorrow, then.

412
00:29:12,638 --> 00:29:16,392
- That would be telling.
- Leeson speaks, the market moves!

413
00:29:16,478 --> 00:29:18,469
You said it, mate.

414
00:29:19,757 --> 00:29:20,712
Pierre.

415
00:29:20,797 --> 00:29:25,109
I want to sell the 220 call options
and buy the 200 calls in December.

416
00:29:25,197 --> 00:29:28,234
I've got an offer of
.138 for size.

417
00:29:28,317 --> 00:29:30,193
Can you do better?

418
00:29:30,276 --> 00:29:31,914
I'll get back to you.

419
00:29:31,996 --> 00:29:34,590
Quick as you can, Nick.
I have to move fast.

420
00:29:35,316 --> 00:29:37,307
Oui, oui, je suis toujours la.

421
00:29:38,555 --> 00:29:41,274
What the hell is he on about,
.138 for size?

422
00:29:41,355 --> 00:29:44,631
The market in 220 calls is down.
He wants to cut his losses.

423
00:29:44,715 --> 00:29:47,388
- Yeah, but why .138?
- It's a ratio.

424
00:29:47,475 --> 00:29:49,749
The 200 calls are
trading at 1,400.

425
00:29:49,834 --> 00:29:53,713
Divide 200 by 1,400,
you get .143.

426
00:29:53,794 --> 00:29:56,183
All right.
But not .138.

427
00:29:56,714 --> 00:30:00,626
Unless someone's offered him a discount.
Probably Societe Generale.

428
00:30:00,713 --> 00:30:03,466
We can't let those wankers
get our biggest client.

429
00:30:03,553 --> 00:30:06,021
- What are you gonna do?
- Just have to leg it.

430
00:30:06,113 --> 00:30:09,661
Buy the contracts from Pierre and
sell them when the market rises?

431
00:30:09,752 --> 00:30:12,744
I thought we were not supposed
to trade for the bank.

432
00:30:12,832 --> 00:30:14,788
Pierre? I can do it.
What's the exact size?

433
00:30:14,872 --> 00:30:17,590
6,500? All right, leave it with me.
No problem.

434
00:30:18,311 --> 00:30:21,428
What if the market doesn't rise, uh?
What if it falls?

435
00:30:21,511 --> 00:30:24,901
I've gambled and won before.
I can gamble and win again.

436
00:30:24,991 --> 00:30:28,619
Balls of steel, me old mateys,
and you'd better believe it.

437
00:30:39,509 --> 00:30:42,501
Bonnie, I need you to reopen
the eights account.

438
00:30:43,509 --> 00:30:45,464
We got caned on
Beaumarchais' contracts.

439
00:30:45,548 --> 00:30:48,824
Now the bastard's gone back
to Societe Generale.

440
00:30:48,908 --> 00:30:53,186
Fax Brenda Granger in London. Ask her
for funds to cover the margin payments.

441
00:30:53,268 --> 00:30:55,258
Tell her it's for client positions.

442
00:30:55,347 --> 00:30:57,224
Hello?

443
00:30:57,307 --> 00:30:59,423
It's Simon.
Can you come into my office?

444
00:30:59,507 --> 00:31:00,986
Right away.

445
00:31:01,067 --> 00:31:05,218
Christ, I'd been rumbled!
The only surprise was it'd taken so long.

446
00:31:05,306 --> 00:31:08,378
What was I gonna tell Lisa?
She'd bloody murder me.

447
00:31:08,466 --> 00:31:10,457
Come in.

448
00:31:16,305 --> 00:31:18,057
Congratulations, Nick.

449
00:31:18,145 --> 00:31:21,535
The '93 bonuses are in,
and you're down for 135 grand.

450
00:31:22,865 --> 00:31:25,094
135?
That's fantastic!

451
00:31:25,184 --> 00:31:30,895
Your little operation generated profits of
over 10 million last year. You're a star!

452
00:31:32,304 --> 00:31:36,091
In fact, your figures are so high
they're going to check up on you.

453
00:31:36,183 --> 00:31:38,060
Check up on me?

454
00:31:38,143 --> 00:31:41,101
They're sending Ash Lewis out
for the audit.

455
00:31:42,462 --> 00:31:45,260
Don't worry.
It's purely routine.

456
00:31:45,342 --> 00:31:47,298
Ash Lewis?

457
00:31:47,382 --> 00:31:50,135
She's meant to be a right
ball-breaker, isn't she?

458
00:31:57,741 --> 00:31:59,732
That's our booth.

459
00:32:01,700 --> 00:32:03,497
Filled!
You paid 250.

460
00:32:03,580 --> 00:32:05,411
Hi, Nick.

461
00:32:05,500 --> 00:32:07,491
Ron Baker and Ash Lewis.

462
00:32:07,580 --> 00:32:09,969
Ron is head of Derivatives Trading
in London.

463
00:32:10,060 --> 00:32:12,095
Which I guess makes
me your boss, Nick.

464
00:32:12,179 --> 00:32:15,012
- How do you, Mr Leeson?
- Very well, thank you.

465
00:32:15,099 --> 00:32:17,169
OK
Let's see the action!

466
00:32:19,259 --> 00:32:20,408
Henry!

467
00:32:20,498 --> 00:32:23,888
Who's doing all the business?
We're the biggest, right?

468
00:32:23,978 --> 00:32:26,890
We do a lot of arbitrage,
so we do have a high volume.

469
00:32:26,978 --> 00:32:29,819
We signal orders in to George
in the pit - this is Henry -

470
